Crimée and Sudetenland, same battle?
BRUSSELS – The annexation of Crimea by Russia constitutes the gravest example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is indeed customary today to minimize the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when discussing this episode where Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier yielded to Hitler's claims on Czechoslovakia in an attempt to appease the Führer.
Nevertheless, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might well come to regret their inaction.
Among Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – for example, expelling Russia from the G8 – could make a mockery of the situation if the threat to peace in Europe was not so serious.
Putin views the collapse of the Soviet Union as the greatest disaster of modern times, and the man is relentlessly working to resurrect a fallen Russian empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will need to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
Many of the Russian president's successes within his imperial project have cost him virtually nothing so far.
His initiative for an Eurasian Economic Union has allowed him to win over a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
The Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation has pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here comes the most precious geostrategic trophy – Ukraine – which could very well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the other hand, strong with a suborned and subordinated Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And given that the vast majority of Ukrainians do not aspire to join Putin's empire, it is highly likely that the country led by the Russian president will now be a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
The reaction of the international community must match the level of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Cancelling summits, proposing trade deals, and other participation in forums as unproductive as the G8 will not suffice.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, affecting Russian citizens – who, let us remember, keep re-electing Putin to power – can hope to allow us to see the Kremlin abandon its expansionist trajectory.
What kind of sanctions could these be?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles strait to Russian transportation, as it did after the Russo-Georgian war in 2008.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea to prevent American intervention, though it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Turkey could choose to close the Turkish Straits not only to Russian warships but also to all commercial vessels bound for Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on the Russian economy – as well as on Putin’s military ambitions – would be significant.
Turkey is authorized to close the Straits under an amendment made in 1982 to the Montreux Convention of 1936.
Thus, Turkey could use the same argument invoked by Putin to justify the annexation of Crimea – namely, that he would protect the Russian ethnicities living there – to claim it is protecting its own ethnic relatives, the Tatars, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back mid-flight to head for Kiev to support the new interim government.
The Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who like Putin is no soft touch either, could follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish Straits to Russian transportation – until Putin withdraws his entire force from Crimea so that they return to their bases, namely Sevastopol or back to Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to rely on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia tries to intimidate it.
Secondly, U.S. President Barack Obama could impose the same financial sanctions on Russia as he did on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly crippled the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system to all banks doing business with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
The Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the post-Soviet era of scarcity – to continue his aggressive imperialistic endeavors could come at a great cost to them.
Thirdly, it would be possible for Obama to remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was truly a strategic windfall for China.
In an instant, this empire, which had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the Central Asian states, and Ukraine itself, have become important trading partners for China.
The invasion of Georgia by Russia seriously upset China, as one could observe during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held in the aftermath of the war (this regional grouping of several ex-Soviet states bordering both China and Mother Russia).
Russia tried to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The organization, however, expressed its disagreement.
But the Central Asian countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – could never have risen against the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now up to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The true test of this Chinese claim to be a true and responsible protagonist within the international community will play out very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this clear violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other avenues for sanctions are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas refused or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by Putin's cronies.
This will only happen when the pain has become unbearable, especially for the elites, that this sort of struggle that Putin is leading today will fail.
The price of inaction could prove considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, are counting on America's promise to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Furthermore, when Ukraine renounced its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) would guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one can blame Ukraine if it decides to renuclearize its defense (which it remains capable of doing technologically).
Lorsque Chamberlain revint de Munich, Winston Churchill s’adressa à lui selon la célèbre formule « Vous aviez le choix entre la guerre et le déshonneur.
Vous avez choisi le déshonneur, et vous aurez la guerre. » Obama et les autres dirigeants occidentaux sont aujourd’hui confrontés à un choix similaire.
S’ils venaient à faire le choix du déshonneur, nous pouvons être certains que l’audacieux Poutine finira tôt ou tard par leur servir une nouvelle guerre.
